l, there still exists a struggle between the public's quest for accountability and the government's culture of secrecy. Drawing together the unique perspectives of social scientists, journalists, and access to information (ATI) advocates, Brokering Access explores the history of ATI law and supplies multiple examples of its contemporary application at the federal, provincial, and municipal levels. From restrictions to access of airport security data post-9/11 to censorship under the Access to Information Act to the difficulties of obtaining details on streetscape video surveillance, this book reveals the legal and bureaucratic obstacles citizens face when trying to access government information.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanada. -- Access to Information Act. 0aFreedom of information -- Canada. 0aFreedom of information -- Political aspects -- Canada. 0aFreedom of informationxPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aFreedom of informationzCanada. 0aGovernment information -- Canada. 0aGovernment informationzCanada. 0aOfficial secrets -- Canada. 0aOfficial secretszCanada. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Journalism.2bisacsh1 aBahdi, Reem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBronskill, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavoukian, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDafnos, Tla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickson, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHameed, Yavar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHewitt, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHier, Sean P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarsen, Mike, econtributor.4c